SIMPLE: translate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Translate
<hw>Trans*late"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Translated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Translating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[f. <ets>translatus</ets>,
used as p. p. of <ets>transferre</ets> to transfer, but from a different
root. See <er>Trans-</er>, and <er>Tolerate</er>, and cf.
<er>Translation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bear, carry, or remove,
from one place to another; to transfer; <as>as, to <ex>translate</ex> a
tree</as>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the chapel of St. Catharine of Sienna, they show her head- the
rest of her body being <qex>translated</qex> to Rome.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To change to another condition, position, place, or
office; to transfer; hence, to remove as by death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To remove to heaven without a natural
death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By faith Enoch was <qex>translated</qex>, that he should not see
death; and was not found, because God had <qex>translated</qex>him.</q>
<rj><qau>Heb. xi. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>To remove, as a bishop, from one
see to another.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Fisher, Bishop of Rochester, when the king
would have <xex>translated</xex> him from that poor bishopric to a
better, . . . refused.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Camden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To render into another language; to express the
sense of in the words of another language; to interpret; hence, to
explain or recapitulate in other words.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Translating</qex> into his own clear, pure, and flowing
language, what he found in books well known to the world, but too bulky
or too dry for boys and girls.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To change into another form; to transform.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Happy is your grace,⟦br⟧
That can <qex>translate</qex>the stubbornness of fortune⟦br⟧
Into so quiet and so sweet a style.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To cause to remove from one part
of the body to another; <as>as, to <ex>translate</ex> a
disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To cause to lose senses or recollection; to
entrance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>J. Fletcher.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Translate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Translate
<hw>Trans*late</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a translation; to be
engaged in translation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Translation</ent>⟦br⟧
